cleaned_data.original_text:
#BTC is the first "triple point" asset in history. This is why Bitcoin is the best performing store of value asset in history, and its why the Bitcoin price is likely to be unfathomably high in the future.

"Triple point" means that all three functions of money compete for it. 

The three functions of money are üëá

Store of Value
Its usefulness as a SoV will cause people to store it away and use it as collateral. We see this today, with the majority of the supply being locked away in cold store for years. This dramatically increases Bitcoin's scarcity and exaggerates the impact of the next two functions on BTC's price. 

Medium of Exchange
Its usefulness as a Medium of Exchange will ramp up once the network reaches a critical mass of users, and people grow tired of being stolen from. There will be a point where people refuse to accept any amount of arbitrary fiat trash for any amount of their BTC. That will place enormous demand on the price, as some large portion of the $6.3 trillion dollars per day of global commerce would happen on #Bitcoin. Trade would have to be conducted using whatever #BTC is not locked away in cold storage. 

Unit of Account
Its usefulness as a Unit of Account will mean most goods and services will be priced in #BTC. There would be no need to exchange it for other currencies. And it would promote increased global trade as it cannot be censored, sanctioned, or confiscated. For the first time in history, anyone can trade with anyone else on the planet on a peer-to-peer basis.

Combine these three demand side factors with absolute scarcity and you have a recipe for face-melting price action.

cleaned_data.original_text:
The most feared macro event of them all, the yield curve inversion pivot... could it finally be happening?

#Bitcoin has only seen one of these before, during the 2020 black swan.

Why are people so scared of this?

It is an extremely accurate recession predictor, and now the yield curve is more inverted than ever before, seemingly already pivoting.

What is the pivot?

This happens when the 2 year treasury yield rate starts to outpace the 10 year.

Typically, the longer yield would have a higher rate, but when shorter yields are on the rise it shows investors are flocking to long-term rates and not confident in the short term. This in many cases leads to a recession.

There are many reflections of 2008 housing market crash and the 2000s dot com bubble crash, but not all pivots cause catastrophe.

The 1998 pivot did not end in a recession, and the 90's pivot led to a very mild one.

Who knows the extent of damage to the markets this will cause, there's no way to say for sure. Let's observe.

You are incredibly early to this movement.

#Bitcoin is not volatile. 

The definition of "volatility" is "liability to change rapidly and unpredictably, especially for the worse."

Bitcoin is the opposite of volatile. It is stable. It is constant. It is predictable. It is transparent. #BTC is a ruler for measuring the value of all there is.  

Calling BTC volatile is like saying seismographs are volatile when all they are doing is measuring the volatility of the Earth shaking around them.

A tool used for measurement (a ruler) cannot itself be volatile. It can only measure volatility.

The confusion arises when people attempt to measure the value of BTC with fiat money. You can't accurately measure the value of something with something that is opaque, where the supply is unknown, and whose price is always being manipulated by unelected officials. 

Like a seismograph, #BTC measures the volatility of the world around it.

Haley shamelessly stood by her claim, asserting that the money, intended for humanitarian aid and food, was being used to support terrorism. However, Welker wasted no time in refuting Haley's statement, emphasizing the lack of proof supporting her accusation. Welker also highlighted that Republican candidates and members of Congress began spreading this false attack against President Biden soon after the attacks occurred.

Unfazed by the response, Welker pressed Haley once more on the issue of making baseless accusations without evidence. Haley attempted to divert the conversation by presenting unrelated evidence about the actions of the Iranian people. However, Welker promptly dismissed this diversion, reminding viewers that even the Secretary of State had stated that there was no connection between the money released by the Biden Administration and the attacks. 

Welker's skillful questioning during the interview was commendable, as she challenged Haley's false claims and held her accountable for providing evidence to support her accusations.

#Bitcoin's price is not suppressed, at least not in the way many of you think it is. Here is why. üßµ

#Bitcoin's halving event (when its supply issuance gets cut in half) will occur approximately 190 days from today. See Image 1. 

Let's take a look at where we are today in terms of the upcoming halving and compare that to where we were at the same point in the last halving cycle.

2024 Halving: April 2024
Days out: Approx. 190 days
Today's price (rounded): $27,000
Prior high price: $69,000
Percent off high: -61%

2020 Halving: May 2020
Days out Approx. 190 days out was Nov 2019
Price 190 days out: $7,500
Prior high: $20,000
Percent off high: -63%

190 days out from the halving now, versus 190 days out from the halving in the last cycle is practically identical. 

Where is this price suppression everyone speaks of?  These numbers look like #Bitcoin is right on schedule, doing what it always does, despite all the silly narratives being thrown at it, doesn't it?

What's even more amazing is that if you were to go back 190 from each of #BTC's prior cycles before 2020, you'll find the same numbers. #BTC is generally down 58% to 64% off its prior peak each and every time, 190 days out.

YOUR SILLY NARRATIVES
I  have heard more silly narratives than you can shake a stick at:

1) #BTC has never gone through a Fed interest rate hiking period. When it does it will collapse;

2) #BTC has never gone through a recession. When it does it will collapse;

3) #BTC can never gone through a period in which there was a hostile SEC. When it does it will collapse;

4) #BTC hasn't gone through a period with this much fraud in the industry. When it does it will collapse.

#BITCOIN DOESN'T CARE!
Despite the fastest interest rate hiking period in recorded history, despite the global economy being on the verge of recession, despite the SEC going after Coinbase, Binance, Ethereum and bunch of other CRAPTOcurrencies, despite the fraud from 3AC, Celsius, DoKwon, Alameda, FTX, SBF and despite the collapses of  BlockFi, Voyager and on top of this despite the bankruptcies of Genesis and the like, #Bitcoin bottomed exactly when it always bottoms (image 2), it had the shallowest bear market decline in its entire history (image 3) and to this very day, BTC is off its prior high the same amount it always is at this point in the cycle: -61%.

#BITCOIN IS MATHS, CODE
So much for your silly narratives. #Bitcoin doesn't care. Bitcoin is maths. Bitcoin is code. And maths and code don't succumb to your fanciful imaginations based on theories that you feel have worked on other things. 

Bitcoin is different. It has come to prove a certainty that should have always existed, but does not exist today because of fraud, corruption and manipulation in the system. It has come to end all of that. Get used to being wrong until you finally get this in your head. 

Now, ignore everything you hear and do what you're supposed to do: #stackharder.

I cannot afford to store my wealth in an unpredictable money managed through Excel spreadsheets.

Price predictions are irrelevants.

In my lifetime, #BTC will dematerialize all fiat currencies.   

Everything there is and ever will be divided by 21M or less, including:

1. Cash
2. Debt
3. Real Estate
4. Stocks
5. Gold

You name it.

On this next bull run, #Bitcoin is going to literally melt faces away! 

You can ignore 99% of all "Technical Analysis" noise. 

This all comes down to Supply and Demand. 

When #btc supply dwindles, the price will rise. 

Until then, accumulate and remain patient. 

Don't overthink it, we know where #Bitcoin is headed.

The remarkable thing about #Bitcoin is that despite the internal disagreements, it continues to work flawlessly.

That, in essence, is the crux of it.

I am 99.9% confident that within my lifetime, 

#BTC will be recognized as one of the most significant discoveries in human history.

Perhaps you haven't realized, but the government is not here to save you.

The most powerful tool we possess in this struggle is #Bitcoin.

1. It's not about nations flexing military muscles, but about governments stripping citizens of their freedoms.

2. It's not a dispute over territorial boundaries, but an encroachment on personal property rights. 

3. It's not an arms race in a physical world, but a race to suppress human rights in the digital age.

4. It's not about political alliances and treaties, but about regimes silencing their own people.

5. It's not a competition for global influence, but a struggle against the erosion of civil liberties.

6. It's not about establishing geopolitical dominance, but about infringing on individual privacy rights.

7. It's not an era of cold wars between superpowers, but a chilling time of governments turning against their citizenry.

Adapt your actions accordingly. Study Bitcoin.

#BTC is a black hole. It‚Äôs sucking the monetary premium out of other store or value assets, exactly as Satoshi designed it to do. 

This is a good thing if you‚Äôre a pleb and a bad thing if you‚Äôre using something other than BTC as a SoV. 

On a fiat standard, people understand that their currency is losing value, so they learn to invest in scarce assets like real estate, stocks and gold. 

Trillions of dollars are being ‚Äústored‚Äù in these assets which drives the prices of these assets much higher than they would be if people could save in their fiat currency instead. As a result, these all trade at a massive premium to their utility value. So, it would be a huge win for the plebs if prices trended toward their utility value. Life would be much more affordable. 

The difference between the actual price of an asset and the price that reflects only its utility value is called a ‚Äúmonetary premium‚Äù.  For example, that share of Apple stock might not trade at 36x earnings despite flat growth if people knew their money would preserve its purchasing power. AAPL is overpriced relative to its fundamentals because it‚Äôs a stable company and acts as a good store of value. The price generally stays ahead of inflation, so people buy it without even thinking about it‚Äôs valuation. Apple enjoys a very high monetary premium. Same for a bar of gold or a house. 

But here‚Äôs the thing. None of these ‚Äúhard assets‚Äù were engineered to be a store of value. Humans assigned store of value status to these assets because they were the best available assets for that purpose. 

So what happens when BTC comes along? Bitcoin is the first asset that has been engineered from the ground up to be a store of value asset. It‚Äôs price reflects nothing but 100% pure monetary premium. Can it really be the case that the one asset with zero ‚Äúutility‚Äù can enjoy the largest monetary premium of all? 

Yes. 

It‚Äôs already happening. 

Gold has hardly budged in the last decade, while BTC is up several hundred thousand percent in the same time frame. Some of the money that would have been used to buy gold and boost the price of gold flowed into BTC instead. BTC has already sucked some of the monetary premium out of gold. 

Which asset class is next? Stocks look unattractive from a macro perspective.  Will some of the capital that would have been stored in stocks find it‚Äôs way into BTC if stocks head lower? 

Real estate is still overpriced, especially with rates as high as they have been in 4 decades. Will some of the money that real estate investors have used to buy property flow into BTC instead? 

Bonds look ok, but savvy investors know that real yields are still negative. The market seems to be waking up to that. What happens to bond yields when large amounts of capital that would have gone into bonds goes into BTC instead? 

BTC will absorb a significant portion of the monetary premium from other store or value assets because it‚Äôs better at storing value than the others and it will do the job for longer. 

Do you hear that sucking sound? That‚Äôs the sound of #BTC slowly absorbing the monetary premium out of every other asset, and returning prices to their utility value in BTC terms.

Comencemos a entender una parte fundamental del an√°lisis:

LA DOMINANCIA DE #BTC:
- Lo primero que debemos de entender es que la dominancia de Bitcoin es sencillamente el peso que tiene el activo con respecto a absolutamente todo el resto de criptomonedas. A mayor dominancia, m√°s dinero y m√°s importancia habr√° dentro de Bitcoin, y viceversa.

Ahora centr√°ndonos en las im√°genes, os voy a aclarar un poco las ideas de lo que est√°is viendo. Donde el primer gr√°fico es el precio de $BTC y el segundo es la dominancia.

¬øQu√© significa cada color y cu√°l es la conclusi√≥n en cada gr√°fico?

1. Rojo = Bear Market. Como veis, la dominancia marca un suelo claro y sube o lateraliza mientras el precio de Bitcoin sigue cayendo durante muchos meses.

2. Verde = Bull Run. La dominancia sube hasta alcanzar su m√°ximo de ese ciclo. Obviamente el precio de Bitcoin tambi√©n sube.

Ahora bien, y la parte que m√°s os va a interesar:

3. Lila = Etapa desde el suelo del Bear Market hasta que finaliza ese a√±o natural. Casualmente en ambos ciclos se marc√≥ el suelo del BearMarket en Enero, por lo que el color lila dura hasta Diciembre de ese mismo a√±o.

- Si nos fijamos, durante ese periodo el precio de #BTC sube teniendo un primer rally alcista desde el suelo del mercado bajista, llegando e incluso supero zonas de resistencia claves. 

4. Naranja = Meses anteriores dentro del mismo a√±o donde suceder√° el #Halving de Bitcoin. 

- Claramente tenemos una nueva "coincidencia", y es que tanto la dominancia de BTC como el precio de BTC caen simult√°neamente. Una correcci√≥n que dar√° lugar a la etapa m√°s explosiva del BullRun. 

5. Azul = Etapa desde el Halving hasta que finaliza ese mismo a√±o natural. 

- Esta es la etapa m√°s explosiva para el PRECIO de Bitcoin. Pero NO para su dominancia. De hecho, la dominancia apenas sube ya, m√°s bien se mantiene en rango. 

6. Negro = Etapa final del BullRun antes de iniciar un nuevo mercado bajista.

- Es el derrumbe de la dominancia de Bitcoin, PERO NO DEL PRECIO. El precio sigue subiendo pero de forma "t√≠mida". Esto dar√° lugar a la fase m√°s fuerte para las #altcoins.

stayed because of topics like software, energy, physics, game theory, and (AI).

the things that always stick with me are knowledge and meaningful connections.

I just want to say thank you for being here and interacting.

It means more to me than you can imagine.

I appreciate every single one of you.

It's been a lot of fun, but it's also been incredibly energy-consuming.

My work breaks consist of scrolling through and writing about #Bitcoin.

These past couple of years have been incredibly entertaining!

Stay diligent and study #BTC;

it will change your life in ways that you can't imagine.

cleaned_data.original_text:
The #Bitcoin White Paper was a marketing document to get the attention of cypher punks who had been toying around the with the idea of e-cash for some time. The use of the term "cash" was more relatable to this group than the use of the word "gold" because cypher punks were not typically gold bugs. This was a way to get their attention.

It's a mistake to treat the white paper like the only representation of Satoshi's intentions when it was clearly not fully fleshed out. I have read it. He omitted the block size, the time between blocks, and the supply cap from the white paper.

Clearly the WP was not the entire blueprint for Bitcoin. He probably spent 3 years writing code for Bitcoin, and less than one week writing the white paper. How does it make sense to only focus on the WP? We have to put more weight on the real work that Satoshi did which was writing the source code.

The source code describes a digital store of value, without any utility, and without a ton of capacity on the base layer. Finite supply encourages hodling, not spending. 10 min block times are less than ideal. And so are small blocks. None of these are optimal design decision for a spending currency. They are, however, ideal for a SoV.

Both large blockers and small blockers believe that BTC was designed to be both an MoE and a SoV. Where we differ is priority.

As a small blocker, I believe that Satoshi prioritized its Store of Value attributes because of the way he designed the protocol, and because he was smart enough to know that an emergent currency can never achieve MoE status unless it could overcome the chicken or the egg problem and build a real network of users. The only way to do that is to give people an incentive to buy and hold BTC long before it's ever useful as a medium of exchange. Why do you think all of the faster chains designed to be MoE are still lagging behind #BTC after all these years? 

If people are not incentivized to save in it, it will never reach a critical mass of users. SoV has to come first. It has always been that way with emergent money. Human nature does not change. Why would this phenomenon change? Satoshi knew this. To suggest that Satoshi would prioritize MoE first is to imply that Satoshi didn't know what he was doing. It's insulting. 

If I were wrong, then BCH and BSV would have crushed BTC, as they both fixed the scalability on layer 1. They both supposedly solved the problem that people had, right? Why are they down 99% against BTC?

The world needs a superior store of value more than it needs another fast payment option. #BTC is the very embodiment of Satoshi's vision.

YOU ARE MAGICAL

Bitcoin needs us. For years progress stagnated and the culture decayed.

But this year, something magical happened. All over the world, wizards like yourself got together and TOOK BITCOIN BACK.

Today we‚Äôre returning the favor and giving back to our supporters üßô‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è

THE STORY SO FAR

In early February, a 4MB wizard appeared on the bitcoin chain. Being the largest transaction to ever hit the orange ledger, it caught the attention of wizards and apprentices around the globe.

They answered our call and joined us in the journey to defeat the laser-eye gatekeepers, and bring fun, innovation, and experimentation back to our magical realm.

Soon, tens of thousands of apprentices arrived at the Wizard School. Together, they learned the dark magic of the lightning network, configured their bitcoin nodes, and took many, many showers.

They partied with us, they fought with us, and they made bitcoin magical again.

A LEGO SORCERESS APPEARS

At an enchanted celebration in the majestic realm of New York City, the apprentices answered our calls. They travelled across the land with their wizard outfits, and showed the world the true power of magic.

One of them was @ragzyart, a LEGO artist who wowed us with her amazing witch outfit, her spell-binding bitcoin art, and her support for us on our journey to save bitcoin.

For her bravery, support and brickmanship, we are excited to gift her Taproot Wizard #0235 (inscription number 148,301!)

Thank you @ragzyart! We are proud to have you with us on this mission.

MORE WIZARDS ARE COMING

In the coming days and weeks, we will continue to highlight and celebrate apprentices who have supported the wizard community!

Why #Bitcoin 's Recent Performance Defies Market Expectations

Remember when market sell-offs would drag Bitcoin down? Not anymore! Amid recent financial tremors, BTC's holding steady at $34k - defying gravity!
Bitcoin's resilience at $34k is seriously impressive. What can we expect next?

Technical analysis

#BTC has held $34k solidly without meaningful lower retests. Now forming a pennant-like pattern at the $34.5k resistance. It seems comfortable here.

Despite the S&P sell-off, Bitcoin's avoided its own drop. Serious strength that must be respected, though indicators remain overheated.

The big question is - does BTC trade like a risk asset or a "safe haven" like gold amid upcoming macro events? The answer to this is critical for Bitcoin's trajectory.

RSI and funding rates

RSI is still heavily overbought, suggesting a pullback ahead. But whether that's from current levels or higher prices remains unclear.
Funding rates are positive, now with more spot follow-through. However, high open interest signals lots of leverage in play.

Cryptonary's take

Bitcoin's recent positive action and bullish structure signal further upside. Many call for a retest of $31k-$32k, but that may be the "crowded trade" now with folks under-positioned.

We think $BTC could rally higher from here WITHOUT a lower retest first. It may hold this pennant and break out, with a retest coming later after higher prices entice more buyers.

Retest feels like a crowded play. We see further upside, especially with Bitcoin in a bullish pattern. The next target is perhaps $37.7k.

Action

We like BTC to keep running here. A pullback may be the crowded bet. Consider adding exposure, especially in lagging alts.

#Bitcoin is a software.

This software remains impartial  

1. It has no politics.
2. No military.
3. No CEO.
4. No authoritative stance.
5. No racial bias. 
6. Holds no opinions. 

It operates on trustless mechanisms.

This software represents immutable truth.

#Bitcoin is synonymous with truth.

Before you give opinions on #Bitcoin, you must first understand it. 

Educate yourself before forming or expressing an opinion.

I save in #Bitcoin because I seek an alternative to relying solely on the government for the protection of my money's purchasing power.

Central banks pledge to uphold the value of our currency, yet they frequently falter in this commitment. 

#Bitcoin offers a solution to this problem.

Many governmental policies inadvertently promote increased debt, reduced accountability, wealth disparity, and diminished productivity and prosperity.

Consider this perspective: perhaps there should be an age cap for those in government, say, 65 years.

opt out.

The Bitcoin Layer 2 Thesis

1. Bitcoin is the most reliable, secure foundation to build decentralized applications. At $500B market cap, it is also a large and mostly untapped market.

2. Institutional adoption will result in significant capital inflows to BTC. As Bitcoin ETFs and other investment products are approved, large asset managers could potentially allocate Billions of dollars to the asset class.

3. Bitcoin developer interest is soaring, resulting in new use cases for BTC. As developers create new apps, this drives a feedback loop of more users and network activity, which in turn brings in more capital.

4. Yet, Bitcoin doesn‚Äôt scale. Developers are constrained by slow block times, large fees, and lack of expressivity in Bitcoin script. These features are by design, in order to provide stability at the base layer.

5. Layer 2s like Stacks are needed to improve scalability and programmability for Bitcoin. With ~5 second block times, Bitcoin-finality, and permissionless way to peg in BTC, Stacks is best positioned to help Bitcoin meet this demand.

6. All of these factors are converging along with the Bitcoin Halving coming in early 2024. The Halving, which is a major shelling point for the industry, will drive more attention to Bitcoin and further strengthen network dynamics.

These reasons are why I believe Bitcoin will lead the next bull run. Now is the best time to start building on Bitcoin. If you‚Äôre a founder looking to get started, please get in touch.

Gm friends and happy Friday! ‚òïÔ∏è 

Updated Hyblock Heatmaps and Liquidation Level for BTC, ETH, SOL, OP, LDO & UNFI

The most significant reaction after yesterday's CPI was in the dollar chart.

Consequently, stocks have decreased slightly, but surprisingly, Bitcoin has remained stable. Or, we could say, the interest in this asset/volume was remarkably low.

Now, Bitcoin is still exactly in the mid of the range, and open interest is still high.

It depends on where you draw the lines exactly, but in my chart, Bitcoin has been below the midrange since Wednesday. I have an eye on this line at 26,900 (set an alarm).

Reclaim and retest from above with solid volume would be a sign of strength for me. Look at the liquidation levels, there are interesting areas.

If it gets rejected again and continues downwards, I'll be looking for shorts.

Most importantly, there's the line at 25,965. If Bitcoin goes below that, the structure of higher highs and higher lows breaks, and we're at the beginning of the large liquidation pool.

Once Bitcoin starts that, I can only imagine it going down to at least 25k.

Please take 10 seconds to leave me a comment and give me a like. It helps me a LOT!

Answering your questions and writing updates takes me several hours a day ü´∂

There is not enough Bitcoin left to be bought OTC.

Institutions, billionaires, and large funds are all attempting to acquire Bitcoin, primarily through OTC transactions to avoid affecting the Bitcoin price.

However, there aren't sufficient OTC deals available for them to purchase the amount of Bitcoin they desire. 

They won't buy Bitcoins on exchanges because that would significantly impact the price.

As a result, they will need to slowly accumulate all the Bitcoin they want over time. 

This process takes a considerable amount of time. 

Nevertheless, once their holdings are complete, we are likely to witness substantial price increases once again.

I have heard far too many times that #Bitcoin is too concentrated in the hands of a few. These same people say that BTC is no different than anything else because it's largely hoarded by the rich and the powerful. 

These repeated narratives I come in contact with almost always lack adequate investigation and research. In other words, they are almost always spouted by either those who are too intellectually lazy to verify them or by those who are intellectually dishonest and don't want them refuted. So, I guess this one is left for me to dismantle. üßµ

Image 1 shows a relatively recent snapshot of #Bitcoin's distribution across its network. As you'll see, outside of Satoshi Nakamoto's 1 million+ BTC, there are only five other addresses that hold between 100,000 and 1 million BTC, with the total of those addresses coming in at 779,000 #BTC. This number accounts for only 3.7% of the total supply.

The next stratum up reveals that only 92 addresses hold between 10,000 and 100,000 #BTC. This category is often referred to as the domain of the whales. These whale addresses hold 2.17 million BTC collectively, and it accounts for 10.3% of the total supply.

Let's pause right here. There really is no need to go further. Let's pick apart what we have so far to see if the claim that #BTC is held in a very concentrated way holds water, as it were.

Aside from Satoshi's address(s), the top tier addresses belong to Binance, Coinbase, Bitfinex and an unknown. These companies represent and hold BTC on behalf of tens if not hundreds of millions of individual owners. This is not concentration at all. It's broad distribution in terms of ownership, although it is held or custodied in a concentrated way. That is another topic all together. 

Grayscale (GBTC) and the already established spot Bitcoin ETFs own a total of 819,000 BTC, with GBTC holding the lion's share of that number at 644,000. Again, all of this is on behalf of millions of individuals across the globe.

Publicly traded companies like Microstrategy (MSTR), Robinhood, Tesla, Digital Galaxy, Marathon, Hut 8, and the like, collectively have 254,000 BTC, about 1.2% of the total supply. Again here, these publicly traded companies are just that, holders for the "public." Micheal Saylor's MSTR owns 155,000 on behalf of 1,028 individual stock holders. This is not concentration at all. It's just group buying. 

We haven't even begun to pick apart the government holdings of #Bitcoin yet. These behemoths, theoretically at least, hold BTC on behalf of their entire citizenry. The US and China are the biggest in this category, but collectively all countries hold 245,000 BTC. By the way, how does Ukraine own more BTC than most of all the countries in the world? ü§î O.k, I digress. 

Now I know some billionaires have sizable holdings like Micheal Saylor, the Winklevi Twins and Tim Draper, but that's only four people. 

The point is this. I think most who ignorantly make the claim that #Bitcoin is too concentrated into the hands of a few miss the fact that most addresses represent the ownership of millions to hundreds of millions of individuals. I also think they fail to realize that the distribution of any money always starts off concentrated but gets more widely distributed over time, which is exactly what happened and continues to happen with BTC.  

First there was only Satoshi. That's one. Then Hal Finney. That's two. Now look. Hundreds of millions. If we revisit these numbers two months from now, you'll see even wider distribution.

#Bitcoin is available for anyone today and will ultimately be adopted by everyone. It's doing just fine, spreading itself throughout the world from its starting point, Satoshi Nakamoto. Don't worry about too much concentration. As the price advances higher and higher, so will the distribution get wider and wider. Just don't count on me to contribute to that distribution, because I'm not selling.

Now get to work. #stackharder

The Gann Square predicts either $89,000 or $135,000 for the #Bitcoin top this cycle.

Using the blue 2x1 fan as the fair value line and drawing the end at Nov 28th (Havling Cycles Theory), has nailed Cycle 1 and 3 tops to precision at Gann Square level 4.

Cycle 2 did something a bit different and came slightly above level 5.

With our fair value line almost certainly set for the cycle,  we now have the two predictions for cycle 4 at levels 4 and 5.

135k lines up with both my N28CT price model and Trend Pattern Price model. 90k is slightly above the 5.3 diminishing returns Theory.

Be sure to check out the other posts below for the different price predictions!

cleaned_data.original_text:
#Bitcoin maximalists are correct about 90% of the time (conservatively speaking), 

Honestly, many people should listen to them more. 

Hear me out.

1. The realm of #Bitcoin is indeed intricate and multifaceted.

2. That said, it's essential to grasp the core philosophy that drives Bitcoin maximalists, which is frequently misunderstood.

3. At first glance, #Bitcoin maxis may seem to advocate for the complete replacement of fiat with Bitcoin.

4. However, this stems from a profound belief in the transformational potential of Bitcoin as a decentralized financial system.

5. Their passion is analogous to early Internet evangelists who saw the Web's potential long before its mainstream adoption.

6. Bitcoin's promise lies in its decentralized, borderless nature.

7. Unlike centralized payment systems, Bitcoin is globally accessible, extending financial services to billions without banking infrastructure.

8. This is a dream that maxis deeply resonate with, envisioning a world where financial inclusion is a right, not a privilege.

9. #Bitcoin provides transactions free from potential censorship by governments or corporations.

10. This isn't a mere theoretical advantage; in areas with political unrest or economic instability, Bitcoin has been a beacon of hope.

11. Maxis champion this quality, emphasizing a future where financial autonomy is sacrosanct.

12. Maximalists are often critiqued for overlooking the immediate practicalities in favor of long-term vision.

13. Yet, this is akin to early automobile enthusiasts being criticized because cars couldn't initially match the ubiquity of horse-drawn carriages.

14. Over time, the vision materializes.

15. While #Bitcoin faces criticism, and maxis are sometimes in the line of fire, such discussions are vital.

16. They drive the discourse, foster innovation, and refine the ecosystem.

17. Maxis, with their unwavering belief, often act as the counterbalance, pushing the boundaries of what's possible.

18. The narrative isn't strictly about "replacing" fiat.

19. It's about showcasing an alternative, more inclusive financial paradigm.

20. Maximalists perceive Bitcoin not just as another currency but as a revolution in the making.

21. However, many are also pragmatic, recognizing the value in Bitcoin coexisting and interrelating with current fiat systems.

22. It's important to understand that the maxis' enthusiasm isn't born from mere financial speculation.

23. They believe in a decentralized, equitable future for finance, and #Bitcoin is their chosen vehicle towards that future.

24. Their dedication is a testament to the transformative potential they see.

25. #Bitcoin maximalists, with their fervent advocacy, are crucial advocates in the crypto ecosystem.

26. While their approach may seem radical to some, history is often kind to those who dream big and challenge the status quo.

27. Embracing their perspective might just provide a richer understanding of where the future of finance is headed.

The greatest oversight of the establishment was to upset Satoshi Nakamoto to the extent that Bitcoin was conceived in 2009.

No empire is safe from technological disruption (#Bitcoin)

We have 5,000 years of written records showing that people usually fail to recognize the strategic importance of new technologies.

Not the exception.

Time and time again, 

Empires rise and fall because they keep allowing themselves to be surprised by the emergence of game-changing technologies.

Even more absurdly, 

The people in charge of these empires keep acting like they have an option to refuse or ignore new technologies after they emerge,

1. As if the cat can be put back in the box.

2. As if they live in an isolated bubble completely separated from the rest of the world.

3. As if their empire is the only empire which gets to decide how they‚Äôre going to use this technology. 

Why do rulers keep allowing their empires to be disrupted by new technologies? 

Why do empires keep forfeiting important technological leads over to their adversaries? 

There are several explanations.

1. This thought experiment highlights a national strategic security dilemma that US faces right now.

2. If a new technology aka #Bitcoin does have vital national strategic security implication.

3. This would imply that barriers slowing society down from reaching consensus about the strategic importance of that technology would represent a national strategic security hazard.

The point is that no empire is safe from technological disruption, you must prepare individually.

USAüá∫üá∏ should sit down and study #Bitcoin as a matter of national security...

Adam Back (@adam3us) has a PhD in distributed systems. He is mentioned in the Bitcoin White Paper and is credited with inventing "Proof of Work".

He is arguably one of the most qualified people in the world to try and improve upon #Bitcoin. He spent years trying. This is what he had to say about itüëá

"There's something unusual about Bitcoin. Back in 2013 I spent a fair amount of my spare time trying to find a way to appreciably improve Bitcoin across scalability, fungibility, decentralization, privacy, making it easier to mine on small devices, and other metrics I considered to be metrics of improvement. I looked at changing the design, parameters, and changing the cryptography. 

To my surprise, anything I tried to improve it in one way made it objectively worse in multiple other ways. It made it more complicated, needed more bandwidth, etc. So, I came to think about Bitcoin as existing in a narrow pocket of design space."

Alt coiners, take heed. No one in your camp has the credentials to match those of Adam Back. You will never improve upon Bitcoin. You are wasting your time.

Conclusion: There's basically nothing you can do to improve Bitcoin. Bitcoin is perfection.
